observations.recommendation:
We  recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the following:

General Services Officer and Municipal Engineer expedite the unimplemented 20% DF projects and ensure the timely completion of the 20% DF projects;

Municipal Engineer ensure that the status of all ongoing and completed projects are properly reported in the quarterly report of GPPAs;

Municipal Planning and Development Officer
Coordinate with the implementing offices and specify the expected start date and completion dates of the PPA of 20% DF in the Annual Investment Plan for the concrete basis of other work plans;
Evaluate the technical viability of proposed development projects before appropriation is requested in order to optimize the 20% DF;
Monitor and evaluate the implementation of projects and ensure the adherence to plans, targets and performance indicators;

The implementing offices and Local Finance Committee prepare the Quarterly Physical Report of Operations and Physical and Financial Performance Evaluation Form, respectively, for them to assess the plans, conditions, situations, and targets of projects of 20% DF; and

The Municipal Budget Officer assists the implementing offices of PPAs in the preparation of the required reports stated in the BOM for LGU.

We recommended that Management:
Strictly enforce the adoption and implementation of the Perpetual Inventory System in accordance with Chapter 7 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs to ensure continuous real-time tracking of inventory balances, accurate accounting of movements, and timely recognition of expenses;
Direct the Accounting Office to stop the practice of reversing the beginning inventory balances to Government Equity, which inaccurately treats them as prior-period errors, rather, require the recognition of inventory issuances as expenses during the period in which they are actually consumed or distributed, using the appropriate expense accounts;
Direct the Accounting Office to prohibit the practice of directly charging inventory purchases to expense accounts, rather, require the initial recording of inventory as assets and only recognized as expenses upon actual issuance, ensuring compliance with the matching principle and accurate reporting of financial position;
Require the Accounting Office to cease charging expensed inventory to the Government Equity account, instead, expenses should be recognized as a direct deduction from the relevant inventory account and recorded through the appropriate expense accounts during the period of actual consumption or distribution;
Instruct the Accounting Office to properly classify all inventory procurements under their corresponding categories (e.g., Office Supplies, Drugs and Medicines, Accountable Forms) to ensure accurate tracking, reporting, and budget control;
Direct the Accounting Office to ensure that inventory issuances are recognized through the appropriate contra-asset accounts (e.g., “Office Supplies Expense,” “Drugs and Medicines Expense”), maintaining a clear audit trail and supporting accurate financial statement presentation;
Require the General Services Office (GSO) to prepare and submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) weekly for all categories , as required by NGAS, to facilitate timely and accurate recording of inventory usage and expenses by the Accounting Office;
Direct the Accounting Office and GSO to conduct regular reconciliations between accounting records and actual physical inventory to detect and resolve discrepancies promptly; and
Strictly comply with the procedures outlined in the New Government Accounting System (NGAS), particularly on inventory recording, recognition, and reporting, to ensure consistency, accountability, and integrity of financial data.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Treasurer strictly enforce the timely liquidation and deposit of unexpended balance of cash advances in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 69 of PD 1445;
The Municipal Treasurer ensure the immediate refund of the unexpended balances, totaling ₱70,430.00, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002;
The Municipal Accountant ensure that each liquidation is properly accounted for and corresponds to the related cash advance granted;
The Municipal Accountant ensure that the unexpended balances are refunded timely, and liquidations are properly documented;
Management only allow additional cash advance after the previous cash advance has been fully settled; and
Management strictly complies with the rules and regulations provided under Sections 69 and 89 of PD No. 1445, Item Nos. 4.1.2, 5.2, 5.3, and 5.8 of COA Circular No. 97-002 to ensure the propriety and validity of cash advances and prevent possible loss of funds and misappropriations.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer to submit a detailed written explanation on the absence of key supporting documents, including but not limited to the Inspection and Acceptance Reports (IAR), in the Disbursement Vouchers related to the payments for the Supply, Delivery, and Installation of Centralized Network Infrastructure, emphasizing that such documents are essential to validate the legality, regularity, and completeness of each transaction, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001 and PD No. 1445;
Require the Municipal Accountant to diligently examine and scrutinize all supporting documents attached to Disbursement Vouchers in all future transactions, and to disallow the processing of any disbursement that does not fully satisfy the documentary requirements, in accordance with her duty to certify the completeness and propriety of supporting documents;
Submit a written explanation as to why the Statements of Work Accomplished (SWA) attached to each payment were not certified as correct by the Engineer or Project-In-Charge, nor verified by the Head of Agency or his authorized representative, as required under Annex "E" of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184;
Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC)-Chairman, the Municipal Accountant, and the Contract Management Team to explain in writing why staggered/partial payments were allowed for a goods procurement contract in the absence of a contractually defined payment schedule or supplemental documents (e.g., Payment Schedule, Delivery Breakdown, Milestone Plan);
Instruct the BAC-Chairman to ensure that all future procurement contracts explicitly include clear, enforceable, and detailed payment terms, and that these terms are clearly specified in the Special Conditions of Contract (SCC) to prevent similar issues;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Accountant, and BAC-Chairman to provide a written justification for the advance payment of ₱1,499,850.00 (15% of contract cost) under the Mobilization Billing Fee, in light of the clear prohibition under PD No. 1445 and RA No. 9184, unless presidential approval has been secured, which will serve as basis of our audit action;
Require Management to submit a written explanation detailing the causes of the delay of the full delivery, final system testing, issuance of an Inspection and Acceptance Report (IAR), and confirmation of system functionality, of the Supply, Delivery, and Installation of Centralized Network Infrastructure was not completed within the contract period.
To submit a written justification for the issuance of all checks related to the payments for the procurement of the Supply, Delivery, and Installation of Centralized Network Infrastructure, most especially the Final Billing, despite the absence of full delivery, final system testing, issuance of an Inspection and Acceptance Report (IAR), and confirmation of system functionality, emphasizing that under Section 88(1) of PD No. 1445, no payment, partial or full, shall be made without proper certification of delivery, inspection, and acceptance, and directing them to provide compelling evidence or documentation, if any, which will serve as basis of our audit action; and
Conduct a comprehensive review of all existing procurement contracts to ensure alignment with applicable laws and regulations, particularly on payment terms, delivery requirements, and documentation protocols in accordance with PD 1445, the 2016 RIRR 9184, as amended by the New Government Procurement Act (RA 12009), and COA Circular 2012-001.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer to submit a detailed written explanation on the absence of key supporting documents, including but not limited to the Inspection and Acceptance Reports (IAR), in the Disbursement Vouchers related to the payments for the Supply and Delivery of Digitization of Document Project – Phase 2 (Digitization of Payment  for Collection and Disbursement Process System), emphasizing that such documents are essential to validate the legality, regularity, and completeness of each transaction, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001 and PD No. 1445;
Require the Municipal Accountant to diligently examine and scrutinize all supporting documents attached to Disbursement Vouchers in all future transactions, and to disallow the processing of any disbursement that does not fully satisfy the documentary requirements, in accordance with her duty to certify the completeness and propriety of supporting documents;
Submit a written explanation as to why the Statements of Work Accomplished (SWA) attached to payment of the first billing was not certified as correct by the Engineer or Project-In-Charge, nor verified by the Head of Agency or his authorized representative, as required under Annex "E" of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184;
Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC)-Chairman, the Municipal Accountant, and the Contract Management Team to explain in writing why staggered/partial payments were allowed for a goods procurement contract in the absence of a contractually defined payment schedule or supplemental documents (e.g., Payment Schedule, Delivery Breakdown, Milestone Plan);
Instruct the BAC-Chairman to ensure that all future procurement contracts explicitly include clear, enforceable, and detailed payment terms, and that these terms are clearly specified in the Special Conditions of Contract (SCC) to prevent similar issues;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Accountant, and BAC Secretariat to provide a written justification for the advance payment of ₱749,850.00 (15% of contract cost) under the Mobilization Billing Fee, in light of the clear prohibition under PD No. 1445 and RA No. 9184, unless presidential approval has been secured, and also explain why this amount should not be disallowed in audit;
Require Management to submit a written explanation detailing the causes of the delay or the reasons why the Digitization of Document Project – Phase 2 (Digitization of Payment for Collection and Disbursement Process System) was not completed within the 140-calendar day contract period, as prescribed in the Notice to Proceed dated August 13, 2024;
Strictly enforce the provisions of the contract by imposing liquidated damages of delay in accordance with Annex “D” of the IRR of RA 9184, and evaluate the contractor’s performance for possible termination for default as provided under Section 41 of the same Act;
Establish and strengthen regular monitoring mechanisms to track the implementation and delivery of project milestones, ensuring that each phase of the project is completed according to schedule and specifications; and
Conduct a comprehensive review of all existing procurement contracts to ensure alignment with applicable laws and regulations, particularly on payment terms, delivery requirements, and documentation protocols in accordance with PD 1445, the 2016 RIRR 9184, as amended by the New Government Procurement Act (RA 12009), and COA Circular 2012-001.

We recommended that Management:
Conduct a comprehensive review of all proposed and existing PPAs in the LDRRMAIP to ensure strict alignment with the four DRRM thematic areas, as outlined in NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1;
Strictly enforce compliance with allowable expenditures under COA Circular No. 2012-002 and JMC No. 2013-1 by disallowing transactions or expenditures that are not related to any existing LDRRM program;
Ensure that all procurement activities funded by the LDRRMF are undertaken in accordance with the provisions of existing government procurement law, as well as other applicable procurement laws and regulation;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to return the unutilized financial assistance amounting to ₱44,500.00 and ensure its proper reversion to the LDRRMF Special Trust Fund;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly follow the existing accounting guidelines on the proper recording of welfare goods under inventory prior to distribution, in accordance with NGAS; and
Submit the approved list of recipients, signed acknowledgment receipts, and a summary report of distributed items to properly support the welfare goods expense.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure all disbursements are certified by the Municipal Budget Officer (MBO) to confirm the existence of a legally authorized appropriation, in accordance with Section 344 of the Local Government Code and PD 1445. This certification should be obtained prior to disbursement and included in all financial documentation, to be implemented starting in the next fiscal quarter;
The Municipal Budget Officer implement a separate registry for continuing appropriations to track the status and utilization of funds properly;
Ensure effective coordination between the MBO, Local Accountant, and the Local Treasurer by instituting at least once every semester meeting to review the status of appropriations and reconcile records. These meetings should be documented, and progress should be reported to the Local Chief Executive;
Conduct a comprehensive review of all continuing appropriations, particularly those with unutilized balances, and identify any appropriations dating back to prior years at least every end of the calendar year;
Formally declare savings from completed or discontinued projects and ensure timely reversion to the General Fund. These reverted funds then be subjected to supplemental budgeting in support of other priority programs of the municipality; and
Require regular monitoring and status reporting of Projects/ Programs/Activities from concerned offices. These reports detail implementation progress, including issues and delays, and be submitted at least every end of the semester to the Local Chief Executive, with a copy furnished to the Commission on Audit (COA).

We recommended that Management:
Strictly enforce compliance with COA Circular No. 2012-001 by establishing internal controls that require complete supporting documents — including the Program of Works (POW), Statement of Work Accomplished (SWA) verified by the Municipal Engineer, and daily attendance sheets — as mandatory attachments before the approval and processing of any payroll disbursements;
Ensure that all payrolls are signed by the payees/laborers as proof of actual receipt of payment, and implement post-disbursement verification procedures to validate authenticity;
Ensure that all payrolls are signed by the payees/laborers as proof of actual receipt of payment, and implement post-disbursement verification procedures to validate authenticity;
Enforce the timely liquidation of all cash advances in accordance with COA rules, requiring that all liquidations be supported by properly acknowledged payrolls and verified documents;
Establish a system of cross-verification of employee assignments and project timelines, such as the use of consolidated master lists, to detect and prevent overlapping payroll claims and double compensation;
Conduct a thorough review of payrolls not duly acknowledged by the intended recipients and requiring full restitution of unacknowledged disbursements; and
Require Management to investigate the duplicate payments made for overlapping project periods, and if validated, recover the overpaid amount from the concerned laborers.

We recommended that:

Management coordinate with the system-provider for the repair and maintenance of the system and ensure that additional safeguards and procedures are performed to support continuance of operations in case system is down;

The Municipal Assessor coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for proper reconciliation of their records to come up with a complete and accurate list showing the name of the taxpayers with the amounts due and collectible as a basis in setting up the correct Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax Receivables from taxpayers which is necessary to fairly present the RPT/SET Receivables in the books of the Municipality;

The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant with a certified list of taxpayers with stated amount due and collectible for the year which would be the basis of the latter to set up RPT/SET receivables at the beginning of the accounting period.

The Municipal Accountant should set up RPT/SET Receivables at the beginning of the year based on the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer's Index Cards supported by a duly certified list of taxpayers and the amounts due and collectible for the year and account for all related transactions in the proper accounts to achieve fair presentation of the affected accounts in the Financial Statements;

The Municipal Accountant ensures that recognition of demandable taxes and collection thereof be accounted properly in the RPT/SET Receivables and any delinquent accounts be continuously reported in the books unless subsequently settled; and

The concerned officials adhere strictly to the above-stated law and rules.

